<font color="#FF0000">WHO AM I? WHO IS JOSH? WHO?</font><br>
<tt>Thu Feb  5 22:18:50 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Someone, I think Tom, asked me who I am. I am 51, overweight, father of 4, and work in the Insurance field. Yea I wear a tie and I am a &quot;suit&quot; too.  My kids and my wife make my stomach burn, but so does politics, and memories of the 60's.  <br><br>
I won't mince words, I protested the hell out of the War in Viet Nam, from save Vancouver BC, Canada.  Yes, I fled. I ran for my life, and I have long ago come to terms with that decision. It was right for me.  Much better then the 1-A notice I had, and the 2nd Lew I would end up in the bush. I also admit I was scared to death, and emotionally and politically opposed to the war.  I did so many West Coast protests that I can't remember anymore.  Reading the archives on some of these threads is like getting PTSD too, Spatz may have been there, but so was I, and I think about 100 times more.  It was cool, it was &quot;in&quot;, I got laid, loaded, and had fun. You guys got killed or killed.  Now I see that.<br><br>
Also, now I understand, after reading the posts here, about Iraq.  It is not so FLIP as the media makes it out.  Sending troops into harms way is fuckin serious. I knew it then. I most certainly know it now with twin sons, both 19.  Will I ever ok them to enlist? Hell No. <br><br>
I read Hackworth too, and the Army Times Online, and other sources of alternative news, and I think Iraq could be the next Viet Nam. It would help our already good economy.  After bombing Bagdad for a month, we will have to invade. No choice. American's will have to hunt down and kill off alot of Royals, and then MAYBE the locals, with help, will find their leader, and hang his ass. Then we can stay to build a democracy for them.  Or it can be another BOSNIA.   I bet we get body counts, or bomb counts, on nightly news.  Cuse me, news it ain't, entertainment it is.<br><br>
Had I to do it over again, I might have taken the C.O. route, but my years in the North were not bad.  I returned when I was forgiven by my country for being right, and have done ok. I did not officially apply for &quot;amenesty&quot; so I don't freely give out my name. Somehow, that made me want to puke, I did not need it, but seeing my folks made up my mind for me, and I returned, quietly, and illegally I suppose.  I certainly don't see my face on any Post Office Walls.<br><br>
I truly feel for the 58K who died. Died for political reasons, betrayed at home by the government, not the protestors.  Sure, you guys have the right, the duty, to be pissed off.  BUT, know who you are angry at.  Me, and my fellow protestors, were really on your side then, and now.  And when Iraq begins to become VietNam, will you be joining me on the streets with a sign.  I will sure as hell be out there, will you be joining me.<br><br>
Funny, several of my Friends from those black days still live in Canada, and would never consider a permanent return to the USA. Yet they are the biggest patriots when it come to nuking Iraq.  They don't see the irony, or perhaps, they do.
